

Interest rates on short-term US Treasury bills were mixed in auctions held on Monday with six- month bills rising to the highest level since March 2001.

The US Treasury Department auctioned 17 billion dollars in six- month bills at a discount rate of 4.155 percent, up from 4.125 percent last week. The rate was the highest since these bills brought 4.22 percent on March 19, 2001.

The department also sold 19 billion dollars in three-month bills at a discount rate of 3.870 percent, down from 3.890 percent last week.

Separately, the US Federal Reserve said Monday that the average yield for one-year Treasury bills, a popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 4.32 percent last week from 4.26 percent the previous week.

